    "\n",
    "# What Is Generative AI?\n",
    "\n",
    "Generative AI refers to machine learning models capable of creating **new content** — text, images, code, audio — that was not directly present in the training data.\n",
    "What distinguishes generative models from earlier AI systems is their ability to produce outputs that are **coherent, context-aware, and semantically meaningful**.\n",
    "\n",
    "## Generative vs. Traditional AI\n",
    "\n",
    "Traditional AI systems primarily **classify, detect, optimize, or recommend**.\n",
    "A classifier trained on customer reviews answers: *\"Is this review positive or negative?\"*\n",
    "\n",
    "Generative AI **creates**. A language model trained on text asks:\n",
    "\n",
    "> \"Given what I've learned about language, what should come next?\"\n",
    "\n",
    "Both paradigms share the same roots: **neural networks**.\n",
    "Understanding those roots — from the single neuron of 1943 to the multi-layer perceptron of 1986 — is essential for building intuition about how modern LLMs and GenAI systems work.\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "# The Early History of Neural Networks\n",
    "\n",
    "## The McCulloch-Pitts Neuron (1943)\n",
    "\n",
    "The conceptual journey toward modern AI began in 1943 with Warren McCulloch and Walter Pitts' paper @mcculloch1943logical, *\"A Logical Calculus of the Ideas Immanent in Nervous Activity.\"*\n",
    "\n",
    "McCulloch, a neuroscientist, and Pitts, a logician, proposed that neurons could be modeled as **binary threshold units**: an artificial neuron receives multiple binary inputs, computes a weighted sum, and fires if the sum exceeds a threshold.\n",
    "\n",
    "$$\n",
    "y = \\begin{cases} 1 & \\text{if } \\sum_{i=1}^{n} w_i x_i \\geq \\theta \\\\ 0 & \\text{otherwise} \\end{cases}\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\n",
    "where $x_i$ are input signals, $w_i$ are synaptic weights, and $\\theta$ is the threshold.\n",
    "\n",
    "The profound insight: networks of such neurons could compute **any logical function** — they were Turing complete.\n",
    "However, the weights were manually set (not learned), and the model used hard thresholds rather than smooth activations.\n",
    "\n",
    "## The Perceptron: Learning Emerges (1958)\n",
    "\n",
    "Frank Rosenblatt's 1958 paper @rosenblatt1958perceptron introduced the **perceptron** — a neuron that could *learn from examples* via a simple update rule:\n",
    "\n",
    "$$\n",
    "w_i^{(new)} = w_i^{(old)} + \\eta \\,(t - y)\\, x_i\n",
    "$$ {#eq-001-perceptron-learning}\n",
    "\n",
    "where $\\eta$ is the learning rate, $t$ is the target output, and $y$ is the model's output.\n",
    "\n",
    "This rule embodies a principle that persists in deep learning: **learn from errors** by adjusting weights proportionally to the mistake.\n",
    "Rosenblatt built the Mark I Perceptron — a physical machine that could recognize simple geometric shapes — and the media proclaimed machines might soon rival human intelligence.\n",
    "\n",
    "The perceptron came with a theoretical guarantee: for **linearly separable** problems, the algorithm converges to a solution in finite time.\n",
    "\n",
    "## The XOR Problem and First AI Winter (1969)\n",
    "\n",
    "In 1969, Marvin Minsky and Seymour Papert published *Perceptrons* @minsky1969perceptrons, proving a critical limitation: a single-layer perceptron **cannot solve the XOR problem** because the XOR function is not linearly separable."
