    "More broadly, single-layer perceptrons could only classify **linearly separable patterns** — excluding most real-world problems.\n",
    "Minsky and Papert's critique triggered the **first AI Winter**: funding dried up, and neural network research stagnated through the 1970s.\n",
    "\n",
    "## Backpropagation: Training Deep Networks (1986)\n",
    "\n",
    "The neural network renaissance arrived with @rumelhart1986learning *\"Learning representations by back-propagating errors\"* by Rumelhart, Hinton, and Williams.\n",
    "\n",
    "Backpropagation solved the core problem Minsky and Papert identified: how to train **multi-layer** networks.\n",
    "It applies the **chain rule** of calculus to propagate error signals backward through layers:\n",
    "\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\\frac{\\partial E}{\\partial w_{ij}} =\n",
    "\\frac{\\partial E}{\\partial y_j} \\cdot\n",
    "\\frac{\\partial y_j}{\\partial \\text{net}_j} \\cdot\n",
    "\\frac{\\partial \\text{net}_j}{\\partial w_{ij}}\n",
    "$$ {#eq-002-backpropagation}\n",
    "\n",
    "where $E$ is the loss, $y_j$ is neuron $j$'s output, and $w_{ij}$ is the weight connecting neuron $i$ to $j$.\n",
    "\n",
    "This allowed networks to learn **internal representations** — patterns in hidden layers that emerge from training rather than being hand-engineered.\n",
    "Networks could now solve XOR and other non-linearly separable problems.\n",
    "\n",
    "## Multi-Layer Perceptrons (1986)\n",
    "\n",
    "The backpropagation paper demonstrated that **multi-layer perceptrons (MLPs)** — networks with one or more hidden layers — could be trained reliably.\n",
    "\n",
    "Key advances:\n",
    "\n",
    "- **Hidden layers** learn intermediate representations, not hand-crafted features\n",
    "- **Non-linear activations** (sigmoid, tanh, ReLU) enable complex decision boundaries\n",
    "- Learning is **distributed across layers**: early layers capture simple patterns, deeper layers combine them hierarchically"
